5","Abt 1195":"okolo 1195","abt 1215":"okolo 1215","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1195–":"omkring 1195–Afdød","1185–Female":"1185–Afdød","1195–Male":"1195–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1198–Female":"1198–Afdød","1097–1197":"1097–1197","–1305":"–1305","–Male":"Afdød","1305":"1305","Abt 1195":"omkring 1195","abt 1215":"omkring 1215","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1195–":"circa 1195–Overleden","1185–Female":"1185–Overleden","1195–Male":"1195–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1198–Female":"1198–Overleden","1097–1197":"1097–1197","–1305":"–1305","–Male":"Overleden","1305":"1305","Abt 1195":"circa 1195","abt 1215":"circa 1215","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1195–":"about 1195–Deceased","1185–Female":"1185–Deceased","1195–Male":"1195–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1198–Female":"1198–Deceased","1097–1197":"1097–1197","–1305":"–1305","–Male":"Deceased","1305":"1305","Abt 1195":"about 1195","abt 1215":"about 1215","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Roger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philippe, Alcee, Armand, Laurent, Leonce, Marcel, Yves, Clovis, Fernand, Gilberte, Janvier, Jean Claude.","Scottish, English, North German, French, Walloon, Catalan, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’ +<i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, which was introduced into England by the Normans in the form <i>Rog(i)er</i> and was reinforced by the Old Norse cognate <i>Hróthgeirr</i>.","History: Gabriel Roger from Sainte-Verge in Deux-Sèvres, France, married Marie (de) Lacour in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Rogero","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Cayetano, Jose, Silva.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Rogero</i> (see   Roger  ).","Catalan (<b>Rogeró</b>): from a pet form of the personal name   Roger  ."]},{"name":"Rieck","meanings":["South German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Ru(o)diger</i>, a compound of Old High German <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ (see   Roger  ).","North German: from a short form of a personal name containing the element <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Rjek</b>: nickname from Upper Sorbian <i>rjek</i> ‘hero’. Compare   Reck  ."]},{"name":"Rogelio","meanings":["Spanish; Portuguese (<b>Rogélio</b>): from the personal name <i>Rogelio</i>, Portuguese <i>Rogélio</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Roger  )."]},{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Roger  ."]},{"name":"Rogers","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Roger  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Ruaidhrí</b> (see   Rorie  ).","History: Thomas Rogers (<i>c.</i> 1587–1621), born in London, England, was among the Pilgrim Fathers who sailed on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620. He died during the first winter at Plymouth Colony, but his son Joseph survived and married, and was later joined in MA by his brother John. This name was subsequently brought to North America independently by many different bearers."]},{"name":"Rogel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Jose, Jose Luis, Juan, Marcos, Margarita, Wilfredo, Adilia, Alejandro, Ana Gladys, Ana Maria, Anacleto.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Rogel</i>, an equivalent of French   Roger  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rogelj</b>: nickname or topographic name from <i>rogelj</i> ‘horn, point’, figuratively ‘tall young man’, as a topographic name probably denoting someone who lived e.g. on a horn-shaped spur of a hill. The surname in the form <i>Rogel</i> is found in Slovenia, too, where it is a less common variant."]},{"name":"Prosser","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Rhosier</i> ‘son of Roger’ (see   Roger   and   Rosser  )."]},{"name":"Rogerson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Roger   + <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Ritger","meanings":["Altered form of German and Dutch <b>Rutger</b> or <b>Rütger</b>, from the personal name <i>Rudiger</i> (see   Roger  )."]},{"name":"Rogge","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Bernd, Bernhard, Elke, Hans, Helmut, Wolfgang.","German and Dutch: from a short form of the personal name   Roger  .","North German and Dutch: metonymic occupational name for a grower of rye or a baker of rye bread, from Low German, Dutch <i>rogge</i> ‘rye’."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gruffudd ap Roger was born about 1195, in Montgomeryshire, Wales as the son of Roger ap Dafydd and Catrin ferch Ithel. He married Gwenllian verch Rhirid Flaidd about 1215, in Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1195–":"umbes 1195–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1198–Female":"1198–Surnud","1097–1197":"1097–1197","–1305":"–1305","–Male":"Surnud","1305":"1305","Abt 1195":"umbes 1195","abt 1215":"umbes 1215","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1195–":"noin 1195–Kuollut","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1195–Male":"1195–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1198–Female":"1198–Kuollut","1097–1197":"1097–1197","–1305":"–1305","–Male":"Kuollut","1305":"1305","Abt 1195":"noin 1195","abt 1215":"noin 1215","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom":